# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1808-united-states-presidential-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The first election for Virginia's 5th congressional district took place on February 2, 1789, for a two-year term to commence on March 4 of that year.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In a race that turned on the candidates' positions on the need for amendments (the Bill of Rights) to the recently ratified U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Constitution, James Madison defeated James Monroe for a place in the House of Representatives of the First Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It is the only congressional election in U.S. history in which two future presidents opposed each other.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They put forward Monroe, a young but experienced politician who was a war hero wounded at the 1776 Battle of Trenton, as a candidate for the seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe did not seek the contest, but once drafted campaigned vigorously.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite bitterly cold weather, the two candidates debated outdoors; traveling after one such meeting, Madison suffered frostbite on his face.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although Madison had earlier stated that amendments to the Constitution were not necessary, during the campaign he took the position that they were, but should be proposed by Congress, rather than by an Article V Convention that Anti-Federalists such as Monroe and Henry supported.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison won the election comfortably, to the satisfaction of his supporters such as President-elect George Washington.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The race did not affect Madison's friendship with Monroe, who was elected to the Senate in 1790, and who would serve as Madison's Secretary of State and succeed him as president in 1817.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Madison was born on March 16, 1751 (March 5, 1750, Old Style), at the Belle Grove plantation near Port Conway, Virginia.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He grew up on his parents' estate of Montpelier, and was involved in politics from a young age, serving on the local Committee of Safety at age 23.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He represented Orange County in the Fifth Virginia Convention of 1776.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After service on the Virginia Council of State, where he forged a lifelong friendship with Governor Thomas Jefferson, he was elected to the Second Continental Congress becoming its youngest member.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was one of Virginia's delegates to the Constitutional Convention in 1787, and helped persuade General George Washington to be its chair, which gave the convention the moral authority to propose a new plan of government.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was the originator of the Virginia Plan that became the basis of the federal government proposed by the convention.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Monroe was born April 28, 1758, in Westmoreland County, Virginia, the son of prosperous planters, Spence Monroe and Elizabeth Jones Monroe.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] By 1774, the year he entered the College of William & Mary, both his parents had died.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In early 1776, he joined the Virginia militia and became an officer in the Continental Army, later that year being severely wounded at the Battle of Trenton.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He left Continental service in 1779, and was made a colonel in the state militia.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the war, Monroe studied law under Jefferson and was elected to the House of Delegates in 1782, and to the Congress of the Confederation in New York in 1783, where he sought to expand the powers of that body.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1784, Madison was told by Jefferson that Monroe wanted to begin a correspondence with him, beginning a relationship that would last until Monroe's death in 1831.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men differed over whether their state should ratify the Constitution at the Virginia Ratifying Convention, with Madison in favor and Monroe against.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Opponents deemed the proposed national government to be too powerful, and many wanted a second constitutional convention in order to place limits on it.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite their efforts, Virginia narrowly ratified the Constitution on June 25, 1788.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe, like Jefferson, believed that there needed to be a Bill of Rights protecting fundamental liberties from infringement by the new federal government.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Ratification had not been a major issue in the Virginia legislative elections of 1788, since it was expected to be decided by the Ratifying Convention that had just been chosen by the voters.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] When the General Assembly convened in October 1788, though, it had a majority of Anti-Federalist members, and was led by Henry, a member of the House of Delegates for Prince Edward County.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry sought to avenge the Anti-Federalist defeat at the Ratifying Convention, and also believed Madison would not seek amendments, or would do so in a lukewarm fashion.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On October 31, the General Assembly re-elected Madison to his seat in the lame-duck Confederation Congress, a body that would cease to exist with the coming of the new federal government.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's motives in allowing this are uncertain, with some historians stating it was to keep Madison in New York, far from the elections for Congress taking place in Virginia.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Historian Chris DeRose hypothesizes that Madison's seat there was his if he wanted it, and his acceptance meant that he expected to remain in New York (where the new Congress would convene) and win his seat in Virginia without needing to campaign.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison, who sought election to the House of Representatives, yielded to Washington and the Federalist minority in the legislature and allowed his name to be put forward in the legislature's election for Virginia's two U.S. senators—until 1913, senators were elected by the state legislatures.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry nominated two Anti-Federalists, Richard Henry Lee and William Grayson, while Madison was the sole Federalist named.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry told the General Assembly that Madison was "unworthy of the confidence of the people" and that his election "would terminate in producing rivulets of blood throughout the land".
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's nominees were elected, Lee with 98 votes and Grayson with 86, while the defeated Madison gained 77.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly turned its attention to dividing the state into congressional districts.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's home county, Orange, was placed in a district with seven others, five of which had elected representatives to the Ratifying Convention who had opposed ratification, while Orange and one other had voted in favor and one county's delegation had split its vote.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly required that candidates live in the district, a qualification not found in the federal Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Fauquier County, closely associated with Orange both geographically and economically, had supported ratification, but was excluded despite the efforts of Federalists.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite some stating that Henry had contrived a district in which Madison was sure to be defeated, Thomas Rogers Hunter in a journal article examined the question, and concluded, "the district was compact and bounded on all sides by natural geographic features.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Simply put, Patrick Henry did not attempt to gerrymander James Madison out of a seat in the first U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Congress." Virginia's 5th congressional district consisted of the counties of Albemarle, Amherst, Culpeper, Fluvanna, Goochland, Louisa, Orange and Spotsylvania.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Some of these counties were later divided, so the district that Madison contested also included the present-day counties of Greene, Madison, Nelson and Rappahannock.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] French Strother, a long-time Virginia legislator from Culpeper County who had opposed ratification at the Virginia Convention, was solicited as a candidate to oppose Madison, but declined.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] William Cabell, of Amherst County, was also considered as an Anti-Federalist candidate but Monroe was selected instead.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Both Strother and Cabell threw their support behind Monroe.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A resident of Spotsylvania County, Monroe was reluctant to run against his friend Madison, but was probably encouraged by Henry, George Mason and other Anti-Federalists, though discouraged by his uncle, Joseph Jones.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] His service in the Revolutionary War, and his political service after it, were electoral assets.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The selection of Monroe was enough to worry Washington: "Sorry indeed should I be if Mr.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Federalist Henry Lee wrote to him, "I profess myself pleased with your exclusion from the senate & I wish it may so happen in the lower house [in which case] you will be left qualified to take part in the administration, which is the place proper for you".
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, Henry Lee believed Madison would win, calling Monroe "the beau".
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison disliked electioneering, but realized he would have to campaign hard to win the race.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Fifth District race would be the only congressional election in history to oppose two future U.S. presidents.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The largest issue in the campaign was the question of a Bill of Rights protecting personal freedoms as amendments to the Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's view had been that these were unnecessary as the Federal government had only limited power and that in any event, the new government should be allowed to operate for a time before changes were made to the Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To take such a stance in the campaign would be political suicide, and Madison recognized that there was widespread support for such amendments.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] But he felt it to be important that Congress proposed them, believing that route to be a quicker, easier, and safer means of passage than an Article V convention, which was favored by the Anti-Federalists such as Monroe.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, he was skeptical about the effect of such amendments, calling them "parchment barriers", ineffective if the Federal government was determined to bypass them.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He told the voters that if elected, he would work diligently for the passage of a Bill of Rights.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's earlier stances made it easy to depict him in this light.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge to support a Bill of Rights if elected left the question of direct taxation as the major difference between them.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe believed the power of the Federal government to directly tax the citizens to be not only unnecessary, but injurious to American liberty.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He felt the government could raise money by tariffs, by the sale of public lands, or by borrowing.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison responded that were the Federal government unable to tax citizens directly, tariffs would be the major source of revenue, and this would disproportionately hurt the South, which had few manufactures and imported heavily from overseas.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He also stated that having federal taxes paid in each state would help bind the nation together as giving each a financial stake in the Union's success.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been in New York, helping to wrap up the affairs of the old Congress of the Confederation.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He received letters from other parts of Virginia from those who believed the residency requirement unconstitutional, offering to have him run there, but he preferred to run in his home district, and he declined.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A trip to Virginia on horseback or in a carriage would be personally hard on Madison, then suffering from a bad case of hemorrhoids.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On December 8, 1788, he wrote to Jefferson (who was in Paris) that he would return to Virginia to campaign for his election, a decision prompted in part by warnings from Virginians that he could not win without personally fighting for the seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He arrived at Washington's plantation, Mount Vernon, on December 18, for a visit that lasted until he returned home to Orange County and his estate, Montpelier, just after Christmas.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] From the time Madison arrived in Virginia, the weather was unusually cold and snowy; the candidates often had to speak in freezing conditions, and the last weekend before the election saw 10 inches (250 mm) of snow.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Aware he was not an orator of Henry's quality, Madison launched a letter-writing campaign, advocating for the new Constitution; though initially taken by surprise, Monroe also set out his positions in letters.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It was Madison's intent, in writing to key citizens in each community, both to enlist support, and have the recipients circulate the letters locally or publish them in local newspapers.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] For Monroe's part, according to DeRose, he "poured himself into the campaign with frenetic energy, determined to campaign everywhere, to personally engage voters, and to make liberal use of his pen to correspond with community leaders.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Considering him as being able to render his Country Great Services on this important occasion".
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On January 7, 1789, Virginians chose electors who would vote for the first U.S. president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The districts for this were not coextensive with congressional districts, since Virginia was entitled to 12 electors but only 10 congressmen.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Still, six of the counties in the Fifth District were in the same district for choosing an elector, and the race featured a Federalist and Anti-Federalist, though both were pledged to vote for Washington for president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Goochland and Louisa counties were not in that electoral district, but Buckingham County was.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Federalist, Edward Stevens, was elected, and outpolled his opponent within the Fifth District, but both parties took hope from the result, with the Anti-Federalists cheered by the fact that Stevens had easily taken Spotsylvania County, where the local favorite Monroe would presumably do better.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates sought to appeal to the local religious communities, of which the Baptists were the most influential.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] That community had taken the position that the Constitution did not provide sufficient protection for their religious liberty.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge of support for amendments defused much of the Anti-Federalist anger against him.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men were quite friendly with each other, and decided to travel together between debates, riding from courthouse to courthouse, making speeches before large crowds.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] These debates showed the physical contrast between the tall, athletic Monroe, who had a full head of brown hair, and the short, slender Madison and his receding hairline.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They often rode together, ate together, and lodged in the same room.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 18th century Virginia, Court Day, a different day in each local county, was not only an opportunity for lawyers and judges to try cases, but a social gathering, including fairs, markets, and other events.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates addressed those present, sometimes speaking for hours to the largest crowds they were likely to find during the campaign.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry Lee wrote to Washington three days later, "Mr Madison is gaining ground fast but still he is involved in much doubt & difficulty.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The debate that DeRose deemed perhaps the most significant of the race took place one evening at the Hebron Lutheran Church in Culpeper (today in Madison County).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Lutherans, like the Baptists, had been persecuted in America, and generally voted as a bloc to maximize their influence.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe and Madison attended the worship service, after which there was musical entertainment featuring fiddles.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They and the congregation then went outside, and the two candidates debated on the front porch as the congregation stood in the bitter cold, with snow on the ground, likely for hours.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Riding away afterwards, likely home to Montpelier, Madison suffered a frostbitten nose.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In his old age, former president Madison would tell the story of that night, and point to the left side of his nose, saying he had battle scars.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] White males who were 21 years of age or older and who owned 50 acres (20 ha) of unimproved land or half that with a house were eligible to vote in the Fifth District.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Approximately 5,189 voters formed the district's electorate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Per the 1790 census, there were 11,231 free white males age over 16 in the district, so about half of free white men were able to vote.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The total population (including women, slaves and children) of the district was 91,007, so the electorate made up less than 6% of the total population, and perhaps 12–15% of those aged over 21.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] There was no secret ballot in Virginia elections in 1789; voters entered the local courthouse and publicly declared their votes, to be recorded by a clerk.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The elections were administered by county sheriffs, normally the senior justice of the peace who had not already served in that capacity.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Due to the bitterly cold weather in the Fifth District, the sheriffs in some counties extended voting beyond February 2, allowing more voters to reach their county courthouse.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] This was not authorized by Virginia law, but had also occurred in the voting for presidential electors the previous month.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To get out the vote, Madison's supporters sent wagons around to transport voters to the polls.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They brought one very old man from a distance, and he listened to them talk and asked if the Monroe spoken of was the son of Spence Monroe, formerly of Westmoreland County.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On being told he was, the man declared he would vote for James Monroe, for "I do not know James Madison", but Spence Monroe had once fed him, clothed him and sheltered him.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Once the polls closed, the local sheriff went to the door of the courthouse and proclaimed the result.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It took time for complete results to be compiled; partial returns were printed in newspapers.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On February 10, the sheriffs of the eight counties of the Fifth District met at Albemarle's courthouse, as the county first named in the election statute, to certify the results.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Their returns indicated that Madison won the election with 1,308 votes to 972 for Monroe.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In Madison's home county of Orange, he received 216 votes to Monroe's 9, in Culpeper 256 to Monroe's 103; he won Albemarle County by 69 votes and Louisa by 104.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had given considerable attention to Orange, apparently spending the day of the polls there despite the urgings of some supporters to base himself for the day in a more populous county, and two-thirds of his margin of victory came from Orange.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Strong Baptist support for Madison there contributed to the outcome.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been able to hold down the margin in strongly Anti-Federalist Amherst to 246–145 for Monroe, who also took his home county of Spotsylvania by 74 votes, Fluvanna by 21 and Goochland by 1 vote.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Baptists favored Madison due to his record of support for religious liberty.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the election, Madison wrote to Jefferson, "It was my misfortune to be thrown into a contest with our friend, Col.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The occasion produced considerable efforts among our respective friends.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] According to Stewart, "Barely thirty years old, Monroe had time to make his way.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In the House of Representatives, Madison introduced and guided to passage the amendments that became known as the Bill of Rights.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He broke with Washington over the administration's policies, and allied with Jefferson, helping gain the latter's election to the presidency, and became his Secretary of State in 1801.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although defeated for Congress, Monroe's frequent court appearances as a lawyer kept him in the public eye in Virginia.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1790, after Grayson's death, the General Assembly elected him to the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He served thereafter in a number of offices, including, twice, Governor of Virginia, and in 1811 Madison named Monroe as Secretary of State.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe was elected president in succession to Madison in 1816, taking office the following year.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The **1790–91 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections occurred during the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1790 and 1791, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the nine senators in Class 1.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 25, 1790 elections in Rhode Island.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated before March 4, 1791; ordered by election date.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winners were seated March 4, 1791; ordered by state.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of these elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated after March 4, 1791, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of the senators from Connecticut were Pro-Administration through 1795.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Oliver Ellsworth was re-elected in 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Samuel Johnson resigned March 3, 1791, at the end of the 1st Congress and Roger Sherman was elected June 13, 1791, to finish the term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Charles Carroll won re-election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 20.00%, or 15 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senator, Tristam Dalton sought re-election but was eliminated before the third ballot.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The third ballot saw the election of George Cabot, who had been a member of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The election in New York was held January 19, 1791, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Philip Schuyler's term would expire March 3, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At the State election in April 1790, nominal Federalist majorities were elected to both houses of the 14th New York State Legislature, but many Federalists were friendly to the Democratic-Republican Governor George Clinton, party lines not being drawn very strictly then.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The incumbent Philip Schuyler ran for re-election as the candidate of the Federalist Party.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] New York State Attorney General Aaron Burr was the candidate of the Democratic-Republican Party, but was at that time a rather moderate politician, opposing the ultras of both parties.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Burr was the choice of both the State Senate and the State Assembly, and was declared elected.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler was defeated despite the nominal majority of his party.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Many of the Federalists took the opportunity to show their disapproval of both Schuyler's haughtiness and the financial policies of Alexander Hamilton, the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Secretary of the Treasury and Schuyler's son-in-law.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Besides, the Livingston faction of the Federalist Party felt betrayed after the election of Rufus King over their candidate James Duane in 1789, and now allied themselves with Clinton and later became Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Obs.: Burr had a majority of 5 votes in the Assembly, but the exact number of votes is unclear.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In 1791, the legislature failed to elect due to a disagreement on procedure.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The seat would remain vacant until 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Moses Robinson were elected by the Vermont House of Representatives and Governor and Council in January 1791, anticipating Vermont's admission to the union.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Vermont was admitted as the 14th state on March 4, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The Senate had adjourned on March 3, at the completion of the 1st United States Congress; the 2nd United States Congress held a one-day session on March 4, and was not scheduled to convene again until October 24.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As a result of this congressional schedule Bradley and Robinson had not been seated when the Vermont House of Representatives convened in early October, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At this legislative session, some members suggested that the January election of Bradley and Robinson had been premature, since Vermont had not yet been admitted to the union.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Robinson volunteered to resign the credentials of their January elections; on October 17, the Governor and Council voted again, and selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The House of Representatives then voted a second time, and also selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley was selected for the "short term" (Class 3), which expired on March 3, 1795.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Robinson received the "long term" (Class 1), which expired on March 3, 1797.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Grayson died March 12, 1790, and John Walker was appointed to continue the term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Future President James Monroe was elected in November 1790 to finish the term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Monroe was re-elected in 1791 to the next term, as well.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1808.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican candidate James Madison defeated Federalist candidate Charles Cotesworth Pinckney decisively.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Madison had served as Secretary of State since President Thomas Jefferson took office in 1801.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, who had declined to run for a third term, threw his strong support behind Madison, a fellow Virginian.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Sitting Vice President George Clinton and former Ambassador James Monroe both challenged Madison for leadership of the party, but Madison won his party's nomination and Clinton was renominated as vice president.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists chose to re-nominate Pinckney, a former ambassador who had served as the party's 1804 nominee, again alongside Rufus King.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the unpopularity of the Embargo Act of 1807, Madison won the vast majority of electoral votes outside of the Federalist stronghold of New England.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton received six electoral votes for president from his home state of New York.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first of two instances in American history in which a new president was selected but the incumbent vice president won re-election, the other being in 1828.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Bradley, who had chaired the congressional nominating caucus during the 1804 presidential election, made a call for the 1808 caucus to the 146 Democratic-Republican members of the United States Congress and Federalist allies.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 89 to 94 members of Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] With the support of outgoing President Thomas Jefferson, Secretary of State James Madison won the presidential nomination over opposing candidates James Monroe and Vice President George Clinton.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus voted to give the vice presidential nomination to Clinton over his main opponent John Langdon, although Clinton's supporters believed Clinton would receive the Federalist Party's presidential nomination.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists instead nominated Charles Cotesworth Pinckney that September.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] A committee of fifteen members was selected to manage Madison's campaign.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Seventeen Democratic-Republicans in Congress opposed Madison's selection and the caucus system whose authority to select presidential and vice-presidential candidates was disputed.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe, who was supported by dissident and majority leader John Randolph, was nominated by a group of Virginia Democratic-Republicans (Old Republicans), and although he did not actively try to defeat Madison, he also refused to withdraw from the race.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was also supported by a group of New York Democratic-Republicans for president even as he remained the party's official vice presidential candidate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist caucus met in September 1808 and re-nominated the party's 1804 ticket, which consisted of General Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina and former Senator Rufus King of New York.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only time in American history that a defeated major party renominated its losing ticket for a second time.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The election was marked by opposition to Jefferson's Embargo Act of 1807, a halt to trade with Europe that disproportionately hurt New England merchants and was perceived as favoring France over Britain.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, Jefferson was still very popular with Americans generally and Pinckney was soundly defeated by Madison, though not as badly as in 1804.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received few electoral votes outside of New England.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney retained the electoral votes of the two states that he carried in 1804 (Connecticut and Delaware), and he also picked up New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and three electoral districts in North Carolina besides the two electoral districts in Maryland that he carried earlier.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Except for the North Carolina districts, all of the improvement was in New England.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe won a portion of the popular vote in Virginia and North Carolina, while the New York legislature split its electoral votes between Madison and Clinton.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The popular vote totals used are the elector from each party with the highest total of votes.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The vote totals of Kentucky, North Carolina, and Tennessee appear to be incomplete.
